<h2 class="featurette-heading">
    Chebyshev&apos;s Inequality
</h2>
<p>
    Chebyshev&apos;s Inequality, where
    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="DeGroot, M. H. (2001), “Probability and Statistics”, 3rd edition, Addison-Wesley.">
        [7]
    </button>

    X is a random variable k > 0 is a parameter, &sigma; is the standard deviation and E(X) is the mean (&mu;):

</p>

<pre>
    <p>P(|X - E(X)| &ge; K&sigma;) &le; 1&frasl;K^2</p>
</pre>

<p>
    Sometimes when looking to identify interactions as malicious it is hard to know enough with regards to the expected
    distribution. In this case Chebyshev’s inequality is an ideal choice

    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="DeGroot, M. H. (2001), “Probability and Statistics”, 3rd edition, Addison-Wesley.">
        [7].
    </button>

    Although no assumptions about the distribution are required, we must make sure observations are independent. This
    formula gives an upper bound for the number of data points further than k standard deviations away from the
    population mean

    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="Amidan BG, TA Ferryman, SK Cooley, “Data Outlier Detection using the Chebyshev Theorem”. In 2005 IEEE Aerospace Conference, pp. 1-6. IEEE Conference Publications, Manhattan Beach, CA.">
        [4],
    </button>

    thus Chebyshev’s Inequality states that not more than 1/k^2 of the distribution's values are further than k standard
    deviations away from the mean. With this in mind we are taking data points that are more than k standard deviations
    from the mean to be anomalous

    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="Amidan BG, TA Ferryman, SK Cooley, “Data Outlier Detection using the Chebyshev Theorem”. In 2005 IEEE Aerospace Conference, pp. 1-6. IEEE Conference Publications, Manhattan Beach, CA.">
        [4].
    </button>

    This method is not bullet-proof as anomalies may crop up due to other factors than were expected, such as

    <button type="button"
            class="btn btn-sm reference"
            data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="right"
            title="Amidan BG, TA Ferryman, SK Cooley, “Data Outlier Detection using the Chebyshev Theorem”. In 2005 IEEE Aerospace Conference, pp. 1-6. IEEE Conference Publications, Manhattan Beach, CA.">
        [4]:
    </button>

    Human error, misinterpretation and biased sample data.
</p>

